content:
Certainly! Here's an example of how you might represent product features related to "Social Media" in JSON format. This example includes three different features:

```json
{
  "productFeatures": [
    {
      "featureName": "Post Scheduling",
      "description": "Allows users to schedule posts in advance for automatic publication.",
      "availablePlatforms": ["Web", "iOS", "Android"],
      "maxScheduledPosts": 100
    },
    {
      "featureName": "Analytics Dashboard",
      "description": "Provides insights into engagement metrics and audience growth.",
      "metricsIncluded": ["Likes", "Shares", "Comments", "Follower Growth"],
      "customizableReports": true
    },
    {
      "featureName": "Content Library",
      "description": "A repository for storing and organizing media assets for easy access.",
      "storageLimitGB": 50,
      "supportsFileTypes": ["jpg", "png", "mp4", "pdf"]
    }
  ]
}
```

In this JSON structure:

- `Post Scheduling` allows users to plan and automate their content publishing.
- `Analytics Dashboard` provides users with valuable insights into their content performance and audience engagement.
- `Content Library` helps users manage and organize their media assets efficiently.
